# Always update `update-log.json`

Whenever you make a user-visible change to this app (new feature, theme work, layout change, removed setting, IPC/auth change, polish pass, bug fix the user will notice, etc.), you MUST add an entry to `update-log.json` in the repo root in the same turn as the change.

## How to add an entry

1. Set `updatedAt` at the top of the file to the current ISO timestamp (UTC).
2. Prepend a new object to the front of the `entries` array — newest first.
3. Use this shape:

```json
{
  "id": "ecs-YYYY-MM-DD-short-slug",
  "date": "YYYY-MM-DD",
  "title": "Short user-facing summary (≤ 60 chars)",
  "details": "1–3 sentences describing what changed and why a player/DM should care."
}
```

- `id` must be globally unique. Prefix with `ecs-`, then date, then a kebab-case slug of the change.
- `date` is the day the change shipped (UTC).
- `title` is what shows on the login screen update log — keep it punchy.
- `details` should describe the *user-visible* effect, not the internal refactor. Mention the setting/menu/screen the user touches.

## When to combine vs. split entries

- One coherent feature ships in one entry, even if it touches many files (e.g., "Default theme + layout toggle + tooltips" in a single line).
- Unrelated changes shipped together get separate entries.
- Pure internal refactors with no user impact do not need an entry.

## Don't forget

- The login screen pulls live notes from GitHub (`update-feed.config.json`). The bundled `update-log.json` is the offline fallback. Always update the file in the repo so both paths stay in sync after the user's next push.
- After editing `update-log.json`, do NOT need to run a build just for this — but if you're already building for the code change, keep going as normal.
- Never silently delete or rewrite past entries; only append new ones.
